The Nigeria Labour Congress (NLC) has registered its displeasure over the exclusion of Nigeria from 25 poor countries granted debt relief by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) The Congress in a statement signed by its President Ayuba Wabba said Nigeria should be included on the list of benefiting countries for the Covid-19 relief and debt moratorium based on very cogent reasons. Wabba explained that Nigeria is facing economic crisis given the recent plunge in prices of crude oil, Nigeria’s major foreign earner, saying this has already led to a downsizing of the capital expenditure in the country’s 2020 budget. He said in December, Nigeria external debt hit a 16 year high of US$27 billion with a debt servicing commitment of US$1.5 billiom, adding that the fact that Nigerias debt servicing is about 5 percent of the country’s 2020 federal budget and 75 percent external reserves signpost that the country’s debt servicing pledges are impracticable and should be renegotiated. He argued that with Nigeria being the most populous country in Africa, it could be the epicenter of future wave of Covid-19 if very robust and adequate support is not extended to Nigeria to fight and contain the pandemic. He said, “The Nigeria Labour Congress completely aligns with the position of the International Trade Union Confederation (ITUC) and other international non-governmental organizations which warned that failure to address the debt and financing needs of developing countries could trigger large scale loss of lives and livelihoods. “In order to mobilize the necessary financial resources to fight and defeat Covid-19, the Nigerian labour movement calls for a temporary suspension of debt payments by developing economies, re-negotiation of debt obligations, and ultimately debt pardon by creditor countries. The NLC President advised that the current difficulties instruct the federal government to always keep a healthy debt profile that can withstand the evil day. “While we learn our lessons, we must halt Covid-19, we must re-start our economy, we must pay for essential goods and services, we must recover jobs and income, we must save lives,” he said.